# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: antarctic-microorganism
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:antarctic-microorganism/2024-antarctica-heat-wave] The **2024 Antarctica heat wave** refers to a prolonged and significant mid-winter increase in Antarctic temperatures compared to prior winters, causing several regions of Antarctica to reach temperatures 10 °C (18.0 °F) above normal in July 2024, up to a 28 °C (50.4 °F) increase above average.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/2024-antarctica-heat-wave] The heat wave was significant for occurring during the middle of the Antarctic winter when little to no sunlight shines on the continent, and temperatures are annually at their lowest historically.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/2024-antarctica-heat-wave] In March 2024, a heat wave struck Antarctica that reached 39 °C (70.2 °F) above average.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/2024-antarctica-heat-wave] The increased heat led to a portion of an ice sheet that was roughly "the size of Rome" to fall apart into the Southern Ocean.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/2024-antarctica-heat-wave] Models from climate researchers mapping the areas of the world indicated that the regions most impacted by anthropogenic climate change would be on Earth's poles in the Arctic and the Antarctic.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/2024-antarctica-heat-wave] Prior increases in temperatures in these regions have led to the collapse of Antarctic ice sheets that in turn significantly contribute to rising global sea levels.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/2024-antarctica-heat-wave] Climate researchers found that a weakening in the Antarctic polar vortex, a "band of cold air and low pressure that spins in the stratosphere around each pole", was the primary cause of the heat wave.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/2024-antarctica-heat-wave] Atmospheric scientist Amy Butler reported that the weakening of the polar vortex was caused by atmospheric waves interfering with the vortex, meaning that higher altitude regions in the Antarctic were more susceptible to elevated temperatures.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/2024-antarctica-heat-wave] The disturbances in the polar vortex also caused "massive" quantities of freezing air to be pushed toward the equator, causing unseasonably colder temperatures and cold fronts throughout the Southern Hemisphere, including the Southern Cone of South America, New Zealand, and Australia.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/2024-antarctica-heat-wave] MetDesk director Michael Dukes noted that 2024's El Niño was a significant contributor to increased Antarctic temperatures in addition to anthropogenic climate change.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/2024-antarctica-heat-wave] ETH Zürich climate researcher Jonathan Wille attributed the heatwave to a "really rare" several week long “southern stratospheric warming event” across the continent.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/2024-antarctica-heat-wave] University of Washington atmospheric scientist Edward Blanchard believed that warmer temperatures in the Southern Ocean and decreased sea ice around Antarctica further increased the susceptibility of Antarctica to warmer temperatures during its winter.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/2024-antarctica-heat-wave] In July 2024, a heat wave stuck most of Antarctica, primarily in the Eastern and Central regions of the continent.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/2024-antarctica-heat-wave] Average temperatures were at −4 °C (24.8 °F), extensively higher than average winter temperatures, especially for the time typically associated with Antarctica's coldest annual temperatures.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/2024-antarctica-heat-wave] As a result, the Southern Hemisphere Sea Ice Extent as plotted on a University of Maine Climate Reanalyzer graph reached its second lowest area having at least 15% ice cover on record for its respective day of the year, with only 2023 having a lower area that time of year.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/2024-antarctica-heat-wave] Extrapolation of the graph indicated that 2024 would soon surpass 2023 as the lowest ice cover recorded, potentially in August 2024.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/2024-antarctica-heat-wave] Decreased ice cover was reported to cause a feedback loop involving more sunlight absorbed in areas with less ice cover, further contributing to warming surface temperature and greater areas of melted ice.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/2024-antarctica-heat-wave] Climate researchers predicted that average East Antarctic temperatures from 3 August to 13 August would persist at 36 to 50 degrees Fahrenheit above average, higher than temperatures in the last week of July 2024 that were 12 °C (21.6 °F) above average.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/2024-antarctica-heat-wave] The Amundsen–Scott South Pole Station recorded its warmest average July temperature since 2002 at 6.3 °C (11.3 °F) above average, with an average temperature of −47.6 °C (−53.7 °F) from 20 to 30 July, meeting the average February Antarctic temperature at the typical end of summer.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/2024-antarctica-heat-wave] Vostok, in the center of Antarctica's ice sheet, also recorded its warmest average July temperature since 2009, at 6.4 °C (11.5 °F) above average.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/2024-antarctica-heat-wave] Forecasting director of MetDesk Michael Dukes stated that in addition to recordings of exceptionally high daily temperatures at several individual locations, there was a significantly prolonged rise in average temperatures throughout July 2024, which was more impactful towards the melting of ice.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/2024-antarctica-heat-wave] Berkeley Earth research scientist Zeke Hausfather stated that the Antarctic heat wave was a primary contributor to the hottest days of the planet in meteorological history recorded during July 2024.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/2024-antarctica-heat-wave] University of Washington atmospheric scientist Edward Blanchard called the heat wave a "near-record (or record) event".
[src:antarctic-microorganism/2024-antarctica-heat-wave] Several prominent climate and meteorology researchers expressed feeling pronounced dread and worry over the heat wave.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/2024-antarctica-heat-wave] University of California, San Diego geophysicist Jamin Greenbaum shared his fear towards future Antarctic heat waves and their consequences in the next few years, after noting increasing melt each successive year in East Antarctica while conducting field expeditions.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/2024-antarctica-heat-wave] University of Michigan School for Environment and Sustainability climate scientist Jonathan Overpeck called the heat wave an “eye-opening sign" of how much anthropogenic climate change was impacting Earth.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] Diseases caused by *Acanthamoeba* include keratitis and granulomatous amoebic encephalitis (GAE).
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] The latter is often but not always seen in immunosuppressed patients.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] GAE is caused by the amoebae entering the body through an open wound and then spreading to the brain.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] The combination of host immune responses and secreted amoebal proteases causes massive brain swelling resulting in death in about 95% of those infected.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] Granulomatous amoebic encephalitis (GAE) is caused by amoebic infection of the central nervous system (CNS).
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] It is characterized by neurological symptoms including headache, seizures, and mental-status abnormalities.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] These worsen progressively over weeks to months, leading to death in most patients.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] Infection is generally associated with underlying conditions such as immunodeficiency, diabetes, malignancies, malnutrition, systemic lupus erythematosus, and alcoholism.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] The parasite enters the body through cuts in the skin or by being inhaled into the upper respiratory tract.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] The parasite then spreads through the blood into the CNS.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] *Acanthamoeba* crosses the blood–brain barrier by means that are not yet understood.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] Subsequent invasion of the connective tissue and induction of pro-inflammatory responses leads to neuronal damage that can be fatal within days.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] Pure granulomatous lesions are rare in patients with AIDS and other related immunodeficiency states, as the patients do not have adequate numbers of CD+ve T-cells to mount a granulomatous response to *Acanthamoeba* infection in CNS and other organs and tissues.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] A perivascular cuffing with amoebae in necrotic tissue is usual finding in the AIDS and related T-cell immunodeficiency conditions.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] Brain biopsy normally reveals severe oedema and hemorrhagic necrosis.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] A patient who has contracted this illness usually displays subacute symptoms, including altered mental status, headaches, fever, neck stiffness, seizures, and focal neurological signs (such as cranial nerve palsies and coma), all leading to death within one week to several months.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] Due to the rarity of this parasite and a lack of knowledge, no good diagnoses or treatments for *Acanthamoeba* infection are now known.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] *Acanthamoeba* keratitis cases in the past have resolved from a therapy consisting of atropine and some other drugs with no antimicrobial effects.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] Recent publications show atropine to interfere with the protist's CHRM1 receptor, causing cell death.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] Infection usually mimics that of bacterial leptomeningitis, tuberculous meningitis, or viral encephalitis.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] The misdiagnosis often leads to erroneous, ineffective treatment.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] In the case that the *Acanthamoeba* is diagnosed correctly, the current treatments, such as amphotericin B, rifampicin, trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole, ketoconazole, fluconazole, sulfadiazine, or albendazole, are only tentatively successful.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] Correct and timely diagnosis, as well as improved treatment methods and an understanding of the parasite, are important factors in improving the outcome of infection by *Acanthamoeba*.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] A paper published in 2013 has shown substantial effects of some FDA-approved drugs with an *in vitro* kill rate above 90%.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] These results were *in vitro* effects, but as the drugs are already approved, human infections can be targeted after dose calculations in clinical trials done with these diverse groups of drugs.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] When present in the eye, *Acanthamoeba* strains can cause acanthamoebic keratitis, which may lead to corneal ulcers or even blindness.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] This condition occurs most often among contact lens wearers who do not properly disinfect their lenses, exacerbated by a failure to wash hands prior to handling the lenses.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] Multipurpose contact lens solutions are largely ineffective against *Acanthamoeba*, whereas hydrogen peroxide-based solutions have good disinfection characteristics.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] The first cure of a corneal infection was achieved in 1985 at Moorfields Eye Hospital.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] In May 2007, Advanced Medical Optics, manufacturer of Complete Moisture Plus Contact Lens Solution products, issued a voluntary recall of their Complete Moisture Plus solutions.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] The fear was that contact lens wearers who used their solution were at higher risk of acanthamoebic keratitis than contact lens wearers who used other solutions.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] The manufacturer recalled the product after the Centers for Disease Control in the United States found that 21 people had possibly received an *Acanthamoeba* infection after using Complete Moisture Plus in the month prior to diagnosis.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] Several species of bacteria that can cause human disease are also able to infect and replicate within *Acanthamoeba* species.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] These include *Legionella pneumophila*, *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*, and some strains of *Escherichia coli* and *Staphylococcus aureus*.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] For some of these bacteria, replication inside *Acanthamoeba* has been associated with enhanced growth in macrophages, and increased resistance to some antibiotics.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] Furthermore, due to the high prevalence of *Acanthamoeba* in the environment, these amoebae have been proposed to serve as an environmental reservoir for some human pathogens.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] This species is able to lyse bacteria and produce a wide range of enzymes, such as cellulases or chitinases, and probably contributes to the breakdown of organic matter in soil, contributing to the microbial loop.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] In addition, *Acanthamoeba* has been used extensively to understand the molecular biology of cell motility and cancer cell dormancy by in-depth exploration of the process of encystation.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] The recently available *Acanthamoeba* genome sequence revealed several orthologs of genes employed in meiosis of sexual eukaryotes.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] This finding suggests that *Acanthamoeba* is capable of some form of meiosis and may be able to undergo sexual reproduction.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] Owing to its ease and economy of cultivation, the Neff strain of *A. castellanii*, discovered in a pond in Golden Gate Park in the 1960s, has been effectively used as a classic model organism in the field of cell biology.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] From just 30 L of simple medium inoculated with *A. castellanii*, about 1 kg of cells can be obtained after several days of aerated culture at room temperature.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] Pioneered in the laboratory of Edward D.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] Korn at the National Institutes of Health (NIH), many important biological molecules have been discovered and their pathways elucidated using the *Acanthamoeba* model.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] *Acanthamoeba* also has served as a model to study the evolution of certain G-proteins.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] This unicellular eukaryote expresses few GPCRs over its cell membrane that serve vital role for the microorganism, structural homology bioinformatics tools have been used to show the presence of a homolog of human M1-muscarinic receptor in *A. castellanii*.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] Blocking these muscarinic receptors in past studies has proven to be amoebicidal in Acanthamoeba spp.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] More recently, voltage-gated calcium channels in *Acanthamoeba* spp.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] (CavAc) have been reported to have similarities with human voltage-gated calcium channels such as TPC-1 and L-type calcium channels and respond to Ca-channel blockers such as loperamide.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] This model microbe has been studied to understand complex neurodegenerative states including Alzheimer's disease.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] Scientists have isolated a neurotransmitter acetylcholine in *Acanthamoeba* and the enzymatic machinery needed for its synthesis.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] The giant viruses *Mimivirus, Megavirus*, and *Pandoravirus* infect *Acanthamoeba*.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] Members of the genus *Acanthamoeba* are unusual in serving as hosts for a variety of giant viruses (that have more than 1000 protein-coding genes; for instance, *Pandoravirus*, which has about 2500 protein-coding genes in its genome).
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] Below is a list of described species of *Acanthamoeba*, with sequence types noted where known.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] Species that have been identified in diseased patients are marked with *.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] From the Greek ἄκανθα *akantha* (spike/thorn), which was added before "amoeba" (change) to describe this organism as having a spine-like structure (**acanthopodia**).
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acanthamoeba] This organism is now well known as **Acanthamoeba**, an amphizoic, opportunistic, and nonopportunistic protozoan protist widely distributed in the environment.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] They are important soil organisms, where they contribute to the mineralization of, for example, aromatic compounds.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] *Acinetobacter* species are a key source of infection in debilitated patients in the hospital, in particular the species *Acinetobacter baumannii*.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] Species of the genus *Acinetobacter* are strictly aerobic, nonfermentative, Gram-negative bacilli.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] They show mostly a coccobacillary morphology on nonselective agar.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] Rods predominate in fluid media, especially during early growth.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] The morphology of *Acinetobacter* species can be quite variable in Gram-stained human clinical specimens, and cannot be used to differentiate *Acinetobacter* from other common causes of infection.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] Most strains of *Acinetobacter*, except some of the *A. lwoffii* strain, grow well on MacConkey agar (without salt).
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] Although officially classified as not lactose-fermenting, they are often partially lactose-fermenting when grown on MacConkey agar.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] They are oxidase-negative, catalase-positive, indole-negative, nonmotile, and usually nitrate-negative.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] Bacteria of the genus *Acinetobacter* are known to form intracellular inclusions of polyhydroxyalkanoates under certain environmental conditions (e.g. lack of elements such as phosphorus, nitrogen, or oxygen combined with an excessive supply of carbon sources).
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] The genus *Acinetobacter* comprises 38 validly named species.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] Identification of *Acinetobacter* species is complicated by lack of standard identification techniques.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] Initially, identification was based on phenotypic characteristics such as growth temperature, colony morphology, growth medium, carbon sources, gelatin hydrolysis, glucose fermentation, among others.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] This method allowed identification of *A. calcoaceticus–A. baumannii* complex by the formation of smooth, rounded, mucoid colonies at 37 °C.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] Closely related species could not be differentiated and individual species such as *A. baumannii* and *Acinetobacter* genomic species 3 could not be positively identified phenotypically.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] Different species of bacteria in this genus can be identified using fluorescence-lactose-denitrification to find the amount of acid produced by metabolism of glucose.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] The other reliable identification test at genus level is chromosomal DNA transformation assay.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] In this assay, a naturally competent tryptophan auxotrophic mutant of *Acinetobacter baylyi* (BD4 trpE27) is transformed with the total DNA of a putative *Acinetobacter* isolate and the transformation mixture is plated on a brain heart infusion agar.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] The growth is then harvested after incubation for 24 h at 30 °C, plating on an *Acinetobacter* minimal agar (AMA), and incubating at 30 °C for 108 h.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] Growth on the AMA indicates a positive transformation assay and confirms the isolate as a member of the genus *Acinetobacter*.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] *E. coli* HB101 and *A. calcoaceticus* MTCC1921T can be used as the negative and positive controls, respectively.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] PFGE, AFLP, and ARDRA are validated common methods in use today because of their discriminative ability.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] However, most recent methods include multilocus sequence typing and multilocus PCR and electrospray ionization mass spectrometry, which are based on amplification of highly conserved housekeeping genes and can be used to study the genetic relatedness between different isolates.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] Of the *Acinetobacter*, *A. baumannii* is the greatest cause of human disease, having been implicated in a number of hospital-acquired infections such as bacteremia, urinary tract infections (UTIs), secondary meningitis, infective endocarditis, and wound and burn infections.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] In particular, *A. baumannii* is frequently isolated as the cause of hospital-acquired pneumonia among patients admitted to the intensive care unit.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] Risk factors include long-term intubation and tracheal or lung aspiration.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] In most cases of ventilator-associated pneumonia, the equipment used for artificial ventilation such as endotracheal tubes or bronchoscopes serve as the source of infection and result in the colonization of the lower respiratory tract by *A. baumannii*.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] In some cases, the bacteria can go on to enter the bloodstream, resulting in bacteremia with mortality rates ranging from 32% to 52%.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] UTIs caused by *A. baumannii* appear to be associated with continuous catheterization, as well as antibiotic therapy.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] *A. baumannii* has also been reported to infect skin and soft tissue in traumatic injuries and postsurgical wounds.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] *A. baumannii* commonly infect burns and may result in complications owing to difficulty in treatment and eradication.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] Though less common, some evidence also links this bacterium to meningitis, most often following invasive surgery, and, in very rare cases, to community-acquired primary meningitis wherein the majority of the victims were children.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] Case reports also link *A. baumannii* to endocarditis, keratitis, peritonitis, and very rarely fatal neonatal sepsis.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] The clinical significance of *A. baumannii* is partially due to its capacity to develop resistance against many available antibiotics.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] Reports indicate that it possesses resistance against broad-spectrum cephalosporins, β-lactam antibiotics, aminoglycosides, and quinolones.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] Resistance to carbapenems is also being increasingly reported.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] *A. baumannii* can survive on the human skin or dry surfaces for weeks and is resistant to a variety of disinfectants, making it particularly easy to spread in a hospital setting.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] Antibiotic resistance genes are often plasmid-borne, and plasmids present in *Acinetobacter* strains can be transferred to other pathogenic bacteria by horizontal gene transfer.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] In healthy individuals, *Acinetobacter* colonies on the skin correlate with low incidence of allergies; *Acinetobacter* is thought to be allergy-protective.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] In November 2004, the CDC reported an increasing number of *A. baumannii* bloodstream infections in patients at military medical facilities in which service members injured in the Iraq/Kuwait region during Operation Iraqi Freedom and in Afghanistan during Operation Enduring Freedom were treated.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] Among one set of isolates from Walter Reed Army Medical Center, 13 (35%) were susceptible to imipenem only, and two (4%) were resistant to all drugs tested.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] One antimicrobial agent, colistin (polymyxin E), has been used to treat infections with multidrug-resistant *A. baumannii*; however, antimicrobial susceptibility testing for colistin was not performed on isolates described in this report.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] Because *A. baumannii* can survive on dry surfaces up to 20 days, they pose a high risk of spread and contamination in hospitals, potentially putting immunocompromised and other patients at risk for drug-resistant infections that are often fatal and, in general, expensive to treat.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] Trials to implement vaccines to prevent Acinetobacter infections were documented.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] Reports suggest this bacterium is susceptible to phage therapy.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] Gene-silencing antisense oligomers in a form called peptide-conjugated phosphorodiamidate morpholino oligomers have also been reported to inhibit growth in tests carried out in animals infected with antibiotic-resistant *A. baumannii*.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] Sulbactam/durlobactam (Xacduro) was approved for medical use in the United States in May 2023.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] Bacterial transformation involves the transfer of DNA from a donor to a recipient bacterium through the intervening liquid medium.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] Recipient bacteria must first enter a special physiological state termed competence to receive donor DNA.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] *A. calcoaceticus* is induced to become competent for natural transformation by dilution of a stationary culture into fresh nutrient medium.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] Competence is gradually lost during prolonged exponential growth and for a period after entrance into the stationary state.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] The DNA taken up may be used to repair DNA damage or as a means to exchange genetic information by horizontal gene transfer.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acinetobacter] Natural transformation in *A. calcoaceticus* may protect against exposure to DNA-damaging conditions in the natural environment of these bacteria, as appears to be the case for other bacterial species capable of transformation.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/actinomycetota] The **Actinomycetota** (previously known as **"Actinobacteria"**) are a diverse phylum of Gram-positive bacteria with high guanine-cytosine content (GC content or G+C content).
[src:antarctic-microorganism/actinomycetota] They are of great importance to land flora because of their contributions to soil systems.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/actinomycetota] In soil, they help decompose organic matter of dead organisms so the molecules can be taken up anew by plants.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/actinomycetota] While this role is also played by fungi, actinomycetota are much smaller and likely do not occupy the same ecological niche.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/actinomycetota] In this role, the colonies often grow extensive mycelia, as fungi do, and the name of an important order of the phylum, Actinomycetales (the actinomycetes), reflects that they were long believed to be fungi.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/actinomycetota] Some soil actinomycetota (such as *Frankia*) live symbiotically with the plants whose roots pervade the soil, fixing nitrogen for the plants in exchange for access to some of the plant's saccharides.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/actinomycetota] Other species, such as many members of the genus *Mycobacterium*, are important pathogens.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/actinomycetota] Beyond the great interest in Actinomycetota for their soil role, much is yet to be learned about them.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/actinomycetota] Although currently understood primarily as soil bacteria, they might be more abundant in fresh waters.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/actinomycetota] Actinomycetota is one of the dominant bacterial phyla and contains one of the largest of bacterial genera: *Streptomyces*.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/actinomycetota] *Streptomyces* and other actinomycetota are major contributors to biological buffering of soils.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/actinomycetota] They are also the source of many antibiotics.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/actinomycetota] Bacteria of the Actinomycetota genus *Bifidobacterium* are the most common in the microbiome of human infants.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/actinomycetota] Although adults have fewer bifidobacteria, intestinal bifidobacteria help maintain the mucosal barrier and reduce lipopolysaccharides in the intestine.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/actinomycetota] Although some of the largest and most complex bacterial cells belong to the Actinomycetota, the group of marine Actinomarinales has been described as possessing the smallest free-living prokaryotic cells.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/actinomycetota] Some Siberian or Antarctic biofilms of these bacteria are said to have the longest lifespan of any organism on Earth, frozen in permafrost at around half a million years ago.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/actinomycetota] Most actinomycetota of medical or economic significance are in class Actinomycetia, and belong to the order Actinomycetales.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/actinomycetota] While many of these cause disease in humans, *Streptomyces* is notable as a source of antibiotics.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/actinomycetota] Of those actinomycetota not in the Actinomycetales, *Gardnerella* is one of the most researched.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/actinomycetota] Classification of *Gardnerella* is controversial, and MeSH catalogues it as both a Gram-positive and Gram-negative organism.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/actinomycetota] Actinomycetota-derived antibiotics that are important in medicine include aminoglycosides, anthracyclines, chloramphenicol, macrolides, tetracyclines, etc.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/actinomycetota] Actinomycetota have high guanine and cytosine content in their DNA.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/actinomycetota] The GC content of actinomycetota can be as high as 70%, though some may have a low GC content.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/actinomycetota] Analysis of glutamine synthetase sequence has been suggested for phylogenetic analysis of the Actinomycetota.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/actinomycetota] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature (LPSN) and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acutuncus-antarcticus] The body size of this species varies from 373.8 - 452.9 μm long, having a smooth cuticle and segmented body that appears white or transparent, and four pairs of legs with claws.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acutuncus-antarcticus] The intestines may appear green in color, due to a herbivorous diet consisting but not limited to cyanobacteria and green algae.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acutuncus-antarcticus] *A. antarcticus* have relatively large eyes and an anterior mouth.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acutuncus-antarcticus] Eggs are laid freely, usually in clusters.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acutuncus-antarcticus] They are mostly white and round, but sometimes they are slightly oval shaped.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acutuncus-antarcticus] On rare occasions, eggs are laid into the exuviae, which is sloughed skin.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acutuncus-antarcticus] The total diameter of the eggs can range from 66 to 103 μm.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acutuncus-antarcticus] The first oviposition event, wherein eggs are laid, is typically observed at an age of 9 to 10 days, however this can range from an age of 6 to 11 days.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acutuncus-antarcticus] Clutch size is normally 3 to 6 eggs with a range from 1 to 6 eggs, and there is an average egg development time of 10 days.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acutuncus-antarcticus] Clutch size starts with about 2 eggs during the initial reproductive events, and increases quickly to the maximum average clutch size at 30 days.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acutuncus-antarcticus] The number of oviposition events varies drastically depending on how long the individual lives; once reproductive age is reached, the interval between oviposition events is 5 to 8 days.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acutuncus-antarcticus] It is speculated that climate change could affect the *Acutuncus antarcticus*.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acutuncus-antarcticus] Experimentation with pan-Antarctic *Acutuncus antarcticus* and exposure to UV radiation, extreme temperatures, and desiccation show how the species responds to these factors.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acutuncus-antarcticus] Hydrated and desiccated tagridades were able to tolerate UV radiation, with desiccated targridades being the most successful in tolerating UV radiation.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acutuncus-antarcticus] The survivorship of both groups were negatively affected when exposed to a combination of extreme temperature and UV radiation, with hydrated targridades being more successful in tolerating the temperature and UV radiation changes.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acutuncus-antarcticus] It was also found that UV radiation has an effect on the reproductive abilities of both groups; the targridades exposed to UV radiation had an increase in egg reabsorption and teratological events.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acutuncus-antarcticus] It was concluded that climate change will negatively affect *Acutuncus antarcticus*.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/acutuncus-antarcticus] Since climate change will occur gradually, unlike in the experimental conditions, *Acutuncus antarcticus* may have a better chance of adapting to the changes caused by climate change.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Algae are polyphyletic as they have multiple evolutionary origins.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Although algae with two-membraned chloroplasts seem to form a paraphyletic group within the clade Archaeplastida, other algae with chloroplasts that have three or more membranes evolved from protists that acquired photosynthesis after engulfing archaeplastids.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Most algae are single-celled organisms without roots, leaves, or stems.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Most are photoautotrophs and the main primary producers of aquatic ecosystems, although some are mixotrophs that derive metabolic energy both from internal photosynthesis and from foraging external nutrients.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Some unicellular algae have become heterotrophs or parasites, relying entirely on external energy sources.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Algae have photosynthetic machinery ultimately derived from cyanobacteria that produce oxygen by splitting water molecules, unlike photosynthetic bacteria.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Fossilized filamentous algae from the Vindhya basin have been dated to 1.6 to 1.7 billion years ago.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Because of the wide range of types of algae, there is a correspondingly wide range of industrial and traditional applications in human society.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Traditional seaweed farming practices have existed for thousands of years and have strong traditions in East Asian food cultures.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] More modern algaculture applications extend the food traditions for other applications, including cattle feed, using algae for bioremediation or pollution control, transforming sunlight into algae fuels or other chemicals used in industrial processes, and in medical and scientific applications.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The singular *alga* is the Latin word for "seaweed" and retains that meaning in English.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Although some speculate that it is related to Latin *algēre*, "be cold", no reason is known to associate seaweed with temperature.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] A more likely source is *alliga*, "binding, entwining".
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The Ancient Greek word for "seaweed" was φῦκος (*phŷkos*), which could mean either the seaweed (probably red algae) or a red dye derived from it.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The Latinization, *fūcus*, meant primarily the cosmetic rouge.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The etymology is uncertain, but a strong candidate has long been some word related to the Biblical פוך (*pūk*), "paint" (if not that word itself), a cosmetic eye-shadow used by the Ancient Egyptians and other inhabitants of the eastern Mediterranean.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] It could be any color: black, red, green, or blue.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The study of algae is most commonly called phycology (from Greek *phykos* 'seaweed'); the term algology is falling out of use.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The algae are a heterogeneous group of mostly photosynthetic organisms that produce oxygen and lack the reproductive features and structural complexity of land plants.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] This concept includes the cyanobacteria, which are prokaryotes, and all photosynthetic protists, which are eukaryotes.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] They contain chlorophyll *a* as their primary photosynthetic pigment, and generally inhabit aquatic environments.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] However, there are many exceptions to this definition.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Many non-photosynthetic protists are included in the study of algae, such as the heterotrophic relatives of euglenophytes or the numerous species of colorless algae that have lost their chlorophyll during evolution (e.g., *Prototheca*).
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Some exceptional species of algae tolerate dry terrestrial habitats, such as soil, rocks, or caves hidden from light sources, although they still need enough moisture to become active.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] A range of algal morphologies is exhibited, and convergence of features in unrelated groups is common.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The only groups to exhibit three-dimensional multicellular thalli are the reds and browns, and some chlorophytes.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Apical growth is constrained to subsets of these groups: the florideophyte reds, various browns, and the charophytes.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The form of charophytes is quite different from those of reds and browns, because they have distinct nodes, separated by internode 'stems'; whorls of branches reminiscent of the horsetails occur at the nodes.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Conceptacles are another polyphyletic trait; they appear in the coralline algae and the Hildenbrandiales, as well as the browns.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Most of the simpler algae are unicellular flagellates or amoeboids, but colonial and nonmotile forms have developed independently among several of the groups.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] In three lines, even higher levels of organization have been reached, with full tissue differentiation.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] These are the brown algae,—some of which may reach 50 m in length (kelps)—the red algae, and the green algae.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The most complex forms are found among the charophyte algae (see Charales and Charophyta), in a lineage that eventually led to the higher land plants.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The innovation that defines these nonalgal plants is the presence of female reproductive organs with protective cell layers that protect the zygote and developing embryo.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Hence, the land plants are referred to as the Embryophytes.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The term algal turf is commonly used but poorly defined.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Algal turfs are thick, carpet-like beds of seaweed that retain sediment and compete with foundation species like corals and kelps, and they are usually less than 15 cm tall.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Such a turf may consist of one or more species, and will generally cover an area in the order of a square metre or more.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Many algae, particularly species of the Characeae, have served as model experimental organisms to understand the mechanisms of the water permeability of membranes, osmoregulation, salt tolerance, cytoplasmic streaming, and the generation of action potentials.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Plant hormones are found not only in higher plants, but in algae, too.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Rhodophyta, Chlorophyta, and Heterokontophyta, the three main algal divisions, have life cycles which show considerable variation and complexity.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] In general, an asexual phase exists where the seaweed's cells are diploid, a sexual phase where the cells are haploid, followed by fusion of the male and female gametes.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Asexual reproduction permits efficient population increases, but less variation is possible.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Commonly, in sexual reproduction of unicellular and colonial algae, two specialized, sexually compatible, haploid gametes make physical contact and fuse to form a zygote.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] To ensure a successful mating, the development and release of gametes is highly synchronized and regulated; pheromones may play a key role in these processes.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Sexual reproduction allows for more variation and provides the benefit of efficient recombinational repair of DNA damage during meiosis, a key stage of the sexual cycle.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] However, sexual reproduction is more costly than asexual reproduction.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Meiosis has been shown to occur in many different species of algae.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Linnaeus, in *Species Plantarum* (1753), the starting point for modern botanical nomenclature, recognized 14 genera of algae, of which only four are currently considered among algae.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] In *Systema Naturae*, Linnaeus described the genera *Volvox* and *Corallina*, and a species of *Acetabularia* (as *Madrepora*), among the animals.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] In 1768, Samuel Gottlieb Gmelin (1744–1774) published the *Historia Fucorum*, the first work dedicated to marine algae and the first book on marine biology to use the then new binomial nomenclature of Linnaeus.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] It included elaborate illustrations of seaweed and marine algae on folded leaves.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Harvey (1811–1866) and Lamouroux (1813) were the first to divide macroscopic algae into four divisions based on their pigmentation.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] This is the first use of a biochemical criterion in plant systematics.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Harvey's four divisions are: red algae (Rhodospermae), brown algae (Melanospermae), green algae (Chlorospermae), and Diatomaceae.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] At this time, microscopic algae were discovered and reported by a different group of workers (e.g., O.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Müller and Ehrenberg) studying the Infusoria (microscopic organisms).
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Unlike macroalgae, which were clearly viewed as plants, microalgae were frequently considered animals because they are often motile.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Even the nonmotile (coccoid) microalgae were sometimes merely seen as stages of the lifecycle of plants, macroalgae, or animals.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Although used as a taxonomic category in some pre-Darwinian classifications, e.g., Linnaeus (1753), de Jussieu (1789), Lamouroux (1813), Harvey (1836), Horaninow (1843), Agassiz (1859), Wilson & Cassin (1864), in further classifications, the "algae" are seen as an artificial, polyphyletic group.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Throughout the 20th century, most classifications treated the following groups as divisions or classes of algae: cyanophytes, rhodophytes, chrysophytes, xanthophytes, bacillariophytes, phaeophytes, pyrrhophytes (cryptophytes and dinophytes), euglenophytes, and chlorophytes.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] With the abandonment of plant-animal dichotomous classification, most groups of algae (sometimes all) were included in Protista, later also abandoned in favour of Eukaryota.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] However, as a legacy of the older plant life scheme, some groups that were also treated as protozoans in the past still have duplicated classifications (see ambiregnal protists).
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] In other cases, some groups were originally characterized as parasitic algae (e.g., *Chlorochytrium*), but later were seen as endophytic algae.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Some filamentous bacteria (e.g., *Beggiatoa*) were originally seen as algae.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Furthermore, groups like the apicomplexans are also parasites derived from ancestors that possessed plastids, but are not included in any group traditionally seen as algae.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The most recent estimate (as of January 2024) documents 50,605 living and 10,556 fossil algal species, according to the online database AlgaeBase.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] They are classified into 15 phyla or divisions.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Some phyla are not photosynthetic, namely Picophyta and Rhodelphidophyta, but they are included in the database due to their close relationship with red algae.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The various algal phyla can be differentiated according to several biological traits.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] They have distinct morphologies, photosynthetic pigmentation, storage products, cell wall composition, and mechanisms of carbon concentration.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Some phyla have unique cellular structures.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] , the most common genus of cyanobacteria.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Among prokaryotes, five major groups of bacteria have evolved the ability to photosynthesize, including heliobacteria, green sulfur and nonsulfur bacteria and proteobacteria.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] However, the only lineage where oxygenic photosynthesis has evolved is in the cyanobacteria, often known as blue-green algae for their blue-green (cyan) coloration.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] They are classified as the phylum Cyanobacteriota or Cyanophyta.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] However, this phylum also includes two classes of non-photosynthetic bacteria: Melainabacteria (also called Vampirovibrionia or Vampirovibrionophyceae) and Sericytochromatia (also known as Blackallbacteria).
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] A third class contains the photosynthetic ones, known as Cyanophyceae (also called Cyanobacteriia or Oxyphotobacteria).
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] As bacteria, their cells lack membrane-bound organelles, with the exception of thylakoids.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Like other algae, cyanobacteria have chlorophyll *a* as their primary photosynthetic pigment.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Their accessory pigments include phycobilins (phycoerythrobilin and phycocyanobilin), carotenoids and, in some cases, *b*, *d*, or *f* chlorophylls, generally distributed in phycobilisomes found in the surface of thylakoids.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] They display a variety of body forms, such as single cells, colonies, and unbranched or branched filaments.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Their cells are commonly covered in a sheath of mucilage, and they also have a typical gram-negative bacterial cell wall composed largely of peptidoglycan.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] They have various storage particles, including cyanophycin as aminoacid and nitrogen reserves, "cyanophycean starch" (similar to plant amylose) for carbohydrates, and lipid droplets.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Their Rubisco enzymes are concentrated in carboxysomes.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] They occupy a diverse array of aquatic and terrestrial habitats, including extreme environments from hot springs to polar glaciers.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Some are subterranean, living via hydrogen-based lithoautotrophy instead of photosynthesis.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Three lineages of cyanobacteria, *Prochloraceae*, *Prochlorothrix* and *Prochlorococcus*, independently evolved to have chlorophylls *a* and *b* instead of phycobilisomes.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Due to their different pigmentation, they were historically grouped in a separate division, Prochlorophyta, as this is the typical pigmentation seen in green algae (e.g., chlorophytes).
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Eventually, this classification became obsolete, as it is a polyphyletic grouping.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Cyanobacteria are included as algae by most phycological sources and by the International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants, although a few authors exclude them from the definition of algae and reserve the term for eukaryotes only.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Eukaryotic algae contain chloroplasts that are similar in structure to cyanobacteria.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Chloroplasts contain circular DNA like that in cyanobacteria and are interpreted as representing reduced endosymbiotic cyanobacteria.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] However, the exact origin of the chloroplasts is different among separate lineages of algae, reflecting their acquisition during different endosymbiotic events.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Many groups contain some members that are no longer photosynthetic.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Some retain plastids, but not chloroplasts, while others have lost plastids entirely.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Primary algae are those with "primary chloroplasts", i.e. chloroplasts with two membranes, evolved through a single symbiogenetic event with an endosymbiont β-cyanobacterium as early as 1.6 Gya during the Mesoproterozoic.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] These algae are mainly grouped in the clade Archaeplastida (meaning "ancient plastid"), which includes the major groups Viridiplantae (green algae *sensu lato* and all land plants) and Rhodophyta (red algae) as well as the minor group Glaucophyta (grey algae).
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Land plants (embryophytes) are pigmented similarly to green algae and likely evolved from the freshwater green algae clade Streptophyta, which is sister taxon to Chlorophyta (green algae *sensu stricto*) and the basal clade Prasinodermophyta.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] There is also a minor group of amoeboid protists with primary plastids evolved via different origin and at a much later date than archaeplastid chloroplasts.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The four species of the euglyphid amoebae genus *Paulinella*, have cyanobionts (known as cyanelles) that perform photosynthesis, likely originated from the endosymbiosis of a α-cyanobacterium (probably an ancestral member of Chroococcales), about 90–140 Mya during the Cretaceous.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Secondary algae are eukaryotes with "secondary chloroplasts", i.e. those evolved from phagocytosis and subsequent endosymbiosis of primary algae (mainly green or red algae) or other secondary algae, thus "stealing" the endosymbionts' photosynthetic capability.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] As a result, these algae have chloroplasts surrounded by three or more membranes, and appeared independently in various distantly related protist lineages.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Two lineages of secondary algae, chlorarachniophytes and euglenophytes have "green" chloroplasts containing chlorophylls *a* and *b*.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Their chloroplasts are surrounded by four and three membranes, respectively, and were probably retained from ingested green algae.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Other groups have "red" chloroplasts containing chlorophylls *a* and *c*, and phycobilins.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The shape can vary; they may be of discoid, plate-like, reticulate, cup-shaped, spiral, or ribbon shaped.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] They have one or more pyrenoids to preserve protein and starch.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The latter chlorophyll type is not known from any prokaryotes or primary chloroplasts, but genetic similarities with red algae suggest a relationship there.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The typical dinoflagellate chloroplast has three membranes, but considerable diversity exists in chloroplasts within the group, and a number of endosymbiotic events apparently occurred.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The Apicomplexa, a group of closely related parasites, also have plastids called apicoplasts, which are not photosynthetic.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The Chromerida are the closest relatives of apicomplexans, and some have retained their chloroplasts.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The three alveolate groups evolved from a common myzozoan ancestor that obtained chloroplasts.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The distribution of algal species has been fairly well studied since the founding of phytogeography in the mid-19th century.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Algae spread mainly by the dispersal of spores analogously to the dispersal of cryptogamic plants by spores.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Spores can be found in a variety of environments: fresh and marine waters, air, soil, and in or on other organisms.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Whether a spore is to grow into an adult organism depends on the species and the environmental conditions where the spore lands.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The spores of freshwater algae are dispersed mainly by running water and wind, as well as by living carriers.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] However, not all bodies of water can carry all species of algae, as the chemical composition of certain water bodies limits the algae that can survive within them.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Marine spores are often spread by ocean currents.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Ocean water presents many vastly different habitats based on temperature and nutrient availability, resulting in phytogeographic zones, regions, and provinces.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] To some degree, the distribution of algae is subject to floristic discontinuities caused by geographical features, such as Antarctica, long distances of ocean or general land masses.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] It is, therefore, possible to identify species occurring by locality, such as "Pacific algae" or "North Sea algae".
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] When they occur out of their localities, hypothesizing a transport mechanism is usually possible, such as the hulls of ships.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] For example, *Ulva reticulata* and *U. fasciata* travelled from the mainland to Hawaii in this manner.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Mapping is possible for select species only: "there are many valid examples of confined distribution patterns." For example, *Clathromorphum* is an arctic genus and is not mapped far south of there.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] For example, according to one standard textbook, in the British Isles, the *UK Biodiversity Steering Group Report* estimated there to be 20,000 algal species in the UK.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Another checklist reports only about 5,000 species.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] and so on, but lacking any scientific basis or reliable sources, these numbers have no more credibility than the British ones mentioned above.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Most estimates also omit microscopic algae, such as phytoplankton.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Algae are prominent in bodies of water, common in terrestrial environments, and are found in unusual environments, such as on snow and ice.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Seaweeds grow mostly in shallow marine waters, less than 100 m (330 ft) deep; however, some such as *Navicula pennata* have been recorded to a depth of 360 m (1,180 ft).
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] A type of algae, *Ancylonema nordenskioeldii*, was found in Greenland in areas known as the 'Dark Zone', which caused an increase in the rate of melting ice sheet.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The same algae was found in the Italian Alps, after pink ice appeared on parts of the Presena glacier.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The various sorts of algae play significant roles in aquatic ecology.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Microscopic forms that live suspended in the water column (phytoplankton) provide the food base for most marine food chains.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] In very high densities (algal blooms), these algae may discolor the water and outcompete, poison, or asphyxiate other life forms.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Algae can be used as indicator organisms to monitor pollution in various aquatic systems.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] In many cases, algal metabolism is sensitive to various pollutants.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Due to this, the species composition of algal populations may shift in the presence of chemical pollutants.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] To detect these changes, algae can be sampled from the environment and maintained in laboratories with relative ease.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Some species of algae form symbiotic relationships with other organisms.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] In these symbioses, the algae supply photosynthates (organic substances) to the host organism providing protection to the algal cells.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The host organism derives some or all of its energy requirements from the algae.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Lichens are defined by the International Association for Lichenology to be "an association of a fungus and a photosynthetic symbiont resulting in a stable vegetative body having a specific structure".
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The fungi, or mycobionts, are mainly from the Ascomycota with a few from the Basidiomycota.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] In nature, they do not occur separate from lichens.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] It is unknown when they began to associate.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] One or more mycobiont associates with the same phycobiont species, from the green algae, except that alternatively, the mycobiont may associate with a species of cyanobacteria (hence "photobiont" is the more accurate term).
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] A photobiont may be associated with many different mycobionts or may live independently; accordingly, lichens are named and classified as fungal species.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The association is termed a morphogenesis because the lichen has a form and capabilities not possessed by the symbiont species alone (they can be experimentally isolated).
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The photobiont possibly triggers otherwise latent genes in the mycobiont.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Trentepohlia is an example of a common green alga genus worldwide that can grow on its own or be lichenised.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Lichen thus share some of the habitat and often similar appearance with specialized species of algae (*aerophytes*) growing on exposed surfaces such as tree trunks and rocks and sometimes discoloring them.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Coral reefs are accumulated from the calcareous exoskeletons of marine invertebrates of the order Scleractinia (stony corals).
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] These animals metabolize sugar and oxygen to obtain energy for their cell-building processes, including secretion of the exoskeleton, with water and carbon dioxide as byproducts.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Dinoflagellates (algal protists) are often endosymbionts in the cells of the coral-forming marine invertebrates, where they accelerate host-cell metabolism by generating sugar and oxygen immediately available through photosynthesis using incident light and the carbon dioxide produced by the host.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Reef-building stony corals (hermatypic corals) require endosymbiotic algae from the genus *Symbiodinium* to be in a healthy condition.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The loss of *Symbiodinium* from the host is known as coral bleaching, a condition which leads to the deterioration of a reef.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Endosymbiontic green algae live close to the surface of some sponges, for example, breadcrumb sponges (*Halichondria panicea*).
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The alga is thus protected from predators; the sponge is provided with oxygen and sugars which can account for 50 to 80% of sponge growth in some species.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Prokaryotic algae, i.e., cyanobacteria, are the only group of organisms where oxygenic photosynthesis has evolved.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The oldest undisputed fossil evidence of cyanobacteria is dated at 2100 million years ago, although stromatolites, associated with cyanobacterial biofilms, appear as early as 3500 million years ago in the fossil record.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Eukaryotic algae are polyphyletic thus their origin cannot be traced back to a single hypothetical common ancestor.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] It is thought that they came into existence when photosynthetic coccoid cyanobacteria got phagocytized by a unicellular heterotrophic eukaryote (a protist), giving rise to double-membranous primary plastids.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Such symbiogenic events (primary symbiogenesis) are believed to have occurred more than 1.5 billion years ago during the Calymmian period, early in Boring Billion, but it is difficult to track the key events because of so much time gap.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] This process of serial cell "capture" and "enslavement" explains the diversity of photosynthetic eukaryotes.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The oldest undisputed fossil evidence of eukaryotic algae is *Bangiomorpha pubescens*, a red alga found in rocks around 1047 million years old.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Recent genomic and phylogenomic approaches have significantly clarified plastid genome evolution, the horizontal movement of endosymbiont genes to the "host" nuclear genome, and plastid spread throughout the eukaryotic tree of life.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] It is accepted that both euglenophytes and chlorarachniophytes obtained their chloroplasts from chlorophytes that became endosymbionts.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] In particular, euglenophyte chloroplasts share the most resemblance with the genus *Pyramimonas*.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] However, there is still no clear order in which the secondary and tertiary endosymbioses occurred for the "chromist" lineages (ochrophytes, cryptophytes, haptophytes and myzozoans).
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Two main models have been proposed to explain the order, both of which agree that cryptophytes obtained their chloroplasts from red algae.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] One model, hypothesized in 2014 by John W.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Stiller and coauthors, suggests that a cryptophyte became the plastid of ochrophytes, which in turn became the plastid of myzozoans and haptophytes.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The other model, suggested by Andrzej Bodył and coauthors in 2009, describes that a cryptophyte became the plastid of both haptophytes and ochrophytes, and it is a haptophyte that became the plastid of myzozoans instead.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] These charophyte algae probably already developed filamentous thalli and holdfasts that superficially resembled plant stems and roots, and probably had an isomorphic alternation of generations.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] They perhaps evolved some 850 mya and might even be as early as 1 Gya during the late phase of the Boring Billion.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Algaculture is a form of aquaculture involving the farming of species of algae.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The majority of algae that are intentionally cultivated fall into the category of microalgae (also referred to as phytoplankton, microphytes, or planktonic algae).
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Global production of farmed aquatic plants, overwhelmingly dominated by seaweeds, grew in output volume from 13.5 million tonnes in 1995, to just over 30 million tonnes in 2016 and 37.8 million tonnes in 2022 and 40 million tonnes in 2024.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] This increase was the result of production expansions led by China, followed by Malaysia, the Philippines, the United Republic of Tanzania, and the Russian Federation.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Cultured microalgae already contribute to a wide range of sectors in the emerging bioeconomy.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Research suggests there are large potentials and benefits of algaculture for the development of a future healthy and sustainable food system.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Seaweed farming or kelp farming is the practice of cultivating and harvesting seaweed.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] In its simplest form farmers gather from natural beds, while at the other extreme farmers fully control the crop's life cycle.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The seven most cultivated taxa are *Eucheuma* spp., *Kappaphycus alvarezii*, *Gracilaria* spp., *Saccharina japonica*, *Undaria pinnatifida*, *Pyropia* spp., and *Sargassum fusiforme*.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] *Eucheuma* and *K. alvarezii* are attractive for carrageenan (a gelling agent); *Gracilaria* is farmed for agar; the rest are eaten after limited processing.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Seaweeds are different from mangroves and seagrasses, as they are photosynthetic algal organisms and are non-flowering.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The largest seaweed-producing countries as of 2022 are China (58.62%) and Indonesia (28.6%); followed by South Korea (5.09%) and the Philippines (4.19%).
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Seaweed farming has frequently been developed to improve economic conditions and to reduce fishing pressure.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) reported that world production in 2019 was over 35 million tonnes.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] North America produced some 23,000 tonnes of wet seaweed.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Alaska, Maine, France, and Norway each more than doubled their seaweed production since 2018*.* As of 2019, seaweed represented 30% of marine aquaculture.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] In 2023, the global seaweed extract market was valued at $16.5 billion, with strong projected growth.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Seaweed farming is a carbon negative crop, with a high potential for climate change mitigation.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The IPCC Special Report on the Ocean and Cryosphere in a Changing Climate recommends "further research attention" as a mitigation tactic.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] World Wildlife Fund, Oceans 2050, and The Nature Conservancy publicly support expanded seaweed cultivation.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] An algae bioreactor is used for cultivating micro or macroalgae.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Algae may be cultivated for the purposes of biomass production (as in a seaweed cultivator), wastewater treatment, CO2 fixation, or aquarium/pond filtration in the form of an algae scrubber.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Algae bioreactors vary widely in design, falling broadly into two categories: open reactors and enclosed reactors.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Open reactors are exposed to the atmosphere while enclosed reactors, also commonly called photobioreactors, are isolated to varying extents from the atmosphere.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Specifically, algae bioreactors can be used to produce fuels such as biodiesel and bioethanol, to generate animal feed, or to reduce pollutants such as NOx and CO2 in flue gases of power plants.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Fundamentally, this kind of bioreactor is based on the photosynthetic reaction, which is performed by the chlorophyll-containing algae itself using dissolved carbon dioxide and sunlight.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The carbon dioxide is dispersed into the reactor fluid to make it accessible to the algae.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The bioreactor has to be made out of transparent material.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] To be competitive and independent from fluctuating support from (local) policy on the long run, biofuels should equal or beat the cost level of fossil fuels.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Here, algae-based fuels hold great promise, directly related to the potential to produce more biomass per unit area in a year than any other form of biomass.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The break-even point for algae-based biofuels is estimated to occur by 2025.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Today, algae are used by humans in many ways; for example, as fertilizers, soil conditioners, and livestock feed.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Aquatic and microscopic species are cultured in clear tanks or ponds and are either harvested or used to treat effluents pumped through the ponds.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Algaculture on a large scale is an important type of aquaculture in some places.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Maerl is commonly used as a soil conditioner.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Algae are used as foods in many countries: China consumes more than 70 species, including *fat choy*, a cyanobacterium considered a vegetable; Japan, over 20 species such as *nori* and *aonori*; Ireland, dulse; Chile, cochayuyo.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Laver is used to make laverbread in Wales, where it is known as *bara lawr*.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] In Korea, green laver is used to make *gim*.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The oils from some algae have high levels of unsaturated fatty acids.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Some varieties of algae favored by vegetarianism and veganism contain the long-chain, essential omega-3 fatty acids, docosahexaenoic acid (DHA) and eicosapentaenoic acid (EPA).
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Fish oil contains the omega-3 fatty acids, but the original source is algae (microalgae in particular), which are eaten by marine life such as copepods and are passed up the food chain.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The natural pigments (carotenoids and chlorophylls) produced by algae can be used as alternatives to chemical dyes and coloring agents.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Carrageenan, from the red alga *Chondrus crispus*, is used as a thickener and stabilizer in milk products.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Agar, a gelatinous substance derived from red algae, has a number of commercial uses.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] It is a good medium on which to grow bacteria and fungi, as most microorganisms cannot digest agar.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Alginic acid, or alginate, is extracted from brown algae.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Its uses range from gelling agents in food, to medical dressings.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Alginic acid also has been used in the field of biotechnology as a biocompatible medium for cell encapsulation and cell immobilization.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Molecular cuisine is also a user of the substance for its gelling properties, by which it becomes a delivery vehicle for flavours.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Between 100,000 and 170,000 wet tons of *Macrocystis* are harvested annually in New Mexico for alginate extraction and abalone feed.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Agricultural Research Service scientists found that 60–90% of nitrogen runoff and 70–100% of phosphorus runoff can be captured from manure effluents using a horizontal algae scrubber, also called an algal turf scrubber (ATS).
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Scientists developed the ATS, which consists of shallow, 30-metre (100 ft) raceways of nylon netting where algae colonies can form, and studied its efficacy for three years.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] They found that algae can readily be used to reduce the nutrient runoff from agricultural fields and increase the quality of water flowing into rivers, streams, and oceans.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Researchers collected and dried the nutrient-rich algae from the ATS and studied its potential as an organic fertilizer.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] They found that cucumber and corn seedlings grew just as well using ATS organic fertilizer as they did with commercial fertilizers.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Algae scrubbers, using bubbling upflow or vertical waterfall versions, are now also being used to filter aquaria and ponds.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The alga *Stichococcus bacillaris* has been seen to colonize silicone resins used at archaeological sites; biodegrading the synthetic substance.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Various polymers can be created from algae, which can be especially useful in the creation of bioplastics.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] These include hybrid plastics, cellulose-based plastics, poly-lactic acid, and bio-polyethylene.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Several companies have begun to produce algae polymers commercially, including for use in flip-flops and in surf boards.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] Even algae is also used to prepare various polymeric resins suitable for coating applications.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/algae] The third island on Kunming Lake at Beijing's Summer Palace is called Zaojian Tang Dao (藻鑒堂島).
[src:antarctic-microorganism/alicyclobacillus-acidocaldarius] A strain of *A. acidocaldarius* has been isolated from thermally heated soils of Mount Rittmann in Antarctica.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/alicyclobacillus-acidocaldarius] The optimum growth temperature for *A. acidocaldarius* is 60-65 °C, and can grow in the 45-70 °C range.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] Antarctica is one of the most physically and chemically extreme terrestrial environments to be inhabited by lifeforms.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] The largest plants are mosses, and the largest animals that do not leave the continent are a few species of insects.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] Although most of the continent is covered by glacial ice sheets, ice-free areas comprising approximately 0.4% of the continental land mass are discontinuously distributed around the coastal margins.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] The McMurdo Dry Valleys region of Antarctica is a polar desert characterized by extremely low annual precipitation (<100 mm (3.9 in)) and an absence of vascular plants and vertebrates; microbial activity dominates biological functioning.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] Mean summer high and winter low temperatures in the dry valleys are −5 °C (23 °F) and −30 °C (−22 °F).
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] Because precipitation is both infrequent and low, seasonal water availability in hydrologically connected soils make areas adjacent to water bodies more hospitable relative to dry upland soils.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] Polar ecosystems are particularly sensitive to climate change, where small changes in temperature result in greater changes in local hydrology, dramatically affecting ecosystem processes.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] Soils in Antarctica are nearly two-dimensional habitats, with most biological activity limited to the top four or five inches by the permanently frozen ground below.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] Environments can be limiting due to soil properties such as unfavorable mineralogy, texture, structure, salts, pH, or moisture relationships.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] Visible sources of organic matter are absent for most of continental Antarctica.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] Dry Valley soil ecosystems are characterized by large variations in temperature and light regimes, steep chemical gradients and a high incidence of solar radiation with an elevated ultraviolet B (UVB) light component.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] Dry Valley soils originate from weathering of bedrock and glacial tills that consist of granites, sandstones, basalts and metamorphic rocks.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] Space within these rocks provide protection for microorganisms against some (but not all) of these conditions: i.e., protection from wind scouring and surface mobility, a reduction in UV exposure, reduced desiccation and enhanced water availability, and thermal buffering.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] Half of the soils in the Dry Valleys have subsurface ice, either as buried massive ice or as ice-cemented soil (permafrost).
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] The permafrost layer is typically within 30 cm (12 in) of the soil surface.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] The harsh environment and low availability of carbon and water support a simplified community of mosses, lichens, and mats of green algae and red, orange, and black cyanobacteria near lakes and ephemeral streams.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] Living among the mats are bacteria, yeasts, molds, and an array of microscopic invertebrates that feed on microbes, algae, and detritus: nematodes, protozoa, rotifers, tardigrades, and occasionally, mites and springtails.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] Even simpler communities exist in the arid soils that occupy the majority of the landscape.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] Microbes in Antarctica adapt to aridity the same way microbes in hot deserts do: when water becomes scarce, the organisms simply dry up, shut down metabolic activity, and wait in a cryptobiotic state until water again becomes available.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] Microbes can also go dormant in a cryptobiotic state known as anhydrobiosis when they become dehydrated due to low water availability.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] A more extreme survival method would be long term natural cryopreservation.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] Samples of permafrost sediments aged 5–10 thousand to 2–3 million years old have been found to contain viable micromycete and bacterial cells.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] Algae is present in almost all ice-free areas and occurs in soils, as epiphytes on mosses, in cyanobacterial mats and in plankton of lakes and ponds.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] It is also possible to find algae associated with rocks or living in the thin film of melted water in the snow patches.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] Presently there are over 300 algal taxa identified on Antarctica, with Bacillariophyceae (Diatoms) and Chlorophyta (Green algae) being the most widespread on Antarctica.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] Diatoms are abundant in aquatic environments decreasing in number in terrestrial habitats.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] Chlorophyta are also important in mats in lakes and ponds but tend to increase their relative importance in terrestrial environments and especially in soils, where they are the densest algal group.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] Xanthophyceae (Yellow-green algae) are an important component of the flora in soils of Antarctica.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] Other algal groups (Dinophyta, Cryptophyta, and Euglenophyta) are mainly limited to freshwater communities of the Dry Valleys.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] Distribution of arthropods is limited to areas of high soil moisture and/or access to water, such as streams, or snow meltwater.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] Carbon appears to be more important than moisture in defining good habitats for nematodes in the Dry Valleys of Antarctica.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] *Scottnema lindsayae*, a microbial feeder and the most abundant and widely distributed metazoan invertebrate, often occurs as the sole metazoan species in the McMurdo Dry Valleys.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] It makes its living eating bacteria and yeast out in the dry, salty soils that dominate the valleys.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] All other invertebrate species are more abundant in moist or saturated soils where algae and moss are more abundant.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] Distribution of most nematode species is correlated negatively with elevation (due to temperature and precipitation) and salinity, and positively with soil moisture, soil organic matter, and nutrient availability.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] *Eudorylaimus* spp. is the second most abundant nematode, followed by *Plectus murrayi* who are the least abundant nematodes.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] *Plectus antarcticus* eats bacteria and prefers living in ephemeral streams.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] An average 2-pound bag of dry valley soils contains approximately 700 nematodes, while the more fertile soil found at higher latitudes on the continent may contain approximately 4,000 nematodes.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] The three species listed below were found in moss-dominated moist soils.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] Typically, the highest numbers of cultured bacteria are from relatively moist coastal soils, compared with the small bacteria communities of dry inland soils.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] Cyanobacteria are found in all types of aquatic habitats and often dominate the microbial biomass of streams and lake sediments.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] *Leptolyngbya frigida* is dominant in benthic mats, and is frequently found in soils and as an epiphyte on mosses.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] *Nostoc commune* can develop to sizes visible to the naked eye if supplied with a thin water film.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] The genus *Gloeocapsa* is one of the few cryptoendolithic taxa with a high adaptation to extreme environmental conditions in rocks of the Dry Valleys.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] Actinomycetota such as *Arthrobacter* spp., *Brevibacterium* spp., and *Corynebacterium* spp. are prominent in the Dry Valleys.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] Thermophilic bacteria have been isolated from thermally heated soils near Mt.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] Bacteria genera found in both air samples and the Antarctic include *Staphylococcus*, *Bacillus*, *Corynebacterium*, *Micrococcus*, *Streptococcus*, *Neisseria*, and *Pseudomonas*.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] Bacteria were also found living in the cold and dark in a lake buried a half-mile deep (0.80 km) under the ice in Antarctica.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] The most abundant are *Acanthamoeba* and *Echinamoeba*.
[src:antarctic-microorganism/antarctic-microorganism] The second group consists of monopodal, worm-like amoebae, the subcylindrical *Hartmannella* and *Saccamoeba*, and the lingulate *Platyamoeba stenopodia* Page.
